<font color="#FF0000">TO CHRIS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Mar 14 18:52:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chris,<br><br>
You have some interesting thoughts. However, it sounds a lot like others from my era that were protestors. Albeit, you don't attack those of us who fought in the war. For that I thank you.<br><br>
But if you would examine history closely, veterans have always been the forgotten and abused. In Washington DC after WW1 Army units were used to disband a peaceful protest by unemployed and destitute veterans. These Army units were led by McAurther.<br><br>
Returning WW2 vets also were forgotten. Many were able to get their jobs back, but it took an act of Congress to assure that.<br><br>
Korean vets often were denied benefits because it was a police action.<br><br>
Now Vietnam vets have had benefits reduced or denied. Many of us suffer from the affects of Agent Orange and other defoliants. Many of us suffer from PTSD. We have to fight kicking and screaming to get care from VA.<br><br>
Today, Gulf war vets are having to deal with chemical agents buried and destroyed. I welcome them to the club. Tehy are members of a long and growing club.<br><br>
What makes this worse is that many complain about how bad our government is but will not take the time to even vote in local elections. The result is the same career politicians you so eloquently describe keep getting re-elected.<br><br>
The vast amjority of this country have not a clue as what this land stands for. We were a nation built out of many nations. Now we have become a country that is bent on destroying each other. I no of no other land where churches are burned to the ground simply because of the color of its members skin.<br><br>
Many Vietnam protestors took their frustrations out on us instead of the politicians that put us there. Maybe this will not happen again.<br><br>
However, nothing will change until the people once again get involved and start voting.<br><br>
Hope you stay around. We can learn from each other. Just try to develop your own thoughts. In your own words. Much of what you said sounded like the words of others.
